[thinking] **Considering annotation usage in Java**
[thinking] 
[thinking] I'm pondering the conflict of "no direct reflection" when it comes to user interactions. It seems I might not be able to include reflection in my tests. However, I can write compile-time smoke tests that instantiate classes and utilize methods with annotated parameters. I need to remember that annotations only affect compile time, so there are no assertions via reflection. It's crucial to test that the code compiles and functions normally without altering method invocation.
[thinking] 
[thinking] **Considering Java Compiler API**
[thinking] 
[thinking] I'm thinking about using the Java Compiler API, but it involves serialization, which seems heavy. Plus, native images might not support the compiler at runtime since the JDK tools could be absent. I wonder if annotation processing at compile-time could be a solution without modifying the build. However, it seems like I shouldn't use direct reflection, so I might need to inspect annotations instead. I need to respect the new test requirements and identify any test dependencies.
[thinking] 
